g, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"that","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Sanjay, Gajanan, Narayan, Narendra, Dinesh, Ganesh, Hari, Kiran, Narayana, Seema, Shrikant, Suresh.","Indian: variant of   Bhatt  , common in the southern states of India."],"variants":[{"name":"Bhatt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Bharat, Kiran, Harish, Nikhil, Praful, Ashok, Atul, Dilip, Harshad, Jitendra, Mahesh, Rajesh.","Indian: Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>bhaṭṭa</i> ‘lord’, based on <i>bhartr-</i> ‘lord, husband’, a derivative of <i>bhar-</i> ‘to bear, support’. See also   Bhatti   and   Bhatia  ."]},{"name":"Bhatti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Muhammad, Mohammed, Abdul, Javed, Rashid, Zia, Hamid, Imtiaz, Khalid, Shahid, Ahsan.  Indian Awtar, Nanak, Niranjan, Ajit, Amrit, Anuradha, Chander, Deepak, Dharam, Dinesh, Harjeet, Jagat.","Pakistani and Indian (Punjab, Rajasthan): Muslim, Rajput, and Sikh name, probably derived from the eponymous ancestor of the Bhatti tribe. Etymologically, the name is related to Sanskrit <i>bhaṭṭa</i> ‘lord’ (see   Bhat  ). This tribe is by far the largest and most widely distributed of the Rajput tribes of the Punjab. There is also an area in the Punjab called Bhattiana, which was once ruled by the Bhattis. Bhatti occurs as a personal name in Sanskrit literature. It was the name of a well-known Sanskrit poet of the 6th century. See also   Bhatt   and   Bhatia  ."]}]},{"name":"Ilk,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): nickname from Middle English <i>milk</i> ‘milk’ (Old English <i>meolc</i>). There are many possible reasons for the use of such a nickname, including milk-white hair, the collecting or selling of milk, and of course the drinking of milk – whether or not taken to indicate effeminacy or spiritlessness.","Sorbian: from a pet form of a personal name such as <i>Miłosław</i>, based on the Slavic element <i>mil</i> ‘gentle, dear’ (from Old Slavic <i>milъ</i>). This surname is found mainly in Germanized forms, such as   Mielke   and   Milke  .","Probably also an Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Milch   ‘milk’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mielke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Erwin, Erna, Kurt, Reinhard, Arno, Erhardt, Ernst, Ewald, Frieda, Fritz.","German (of Slavic origin): from a Germanized pet form of any of various Old Slavic personal names, such as <i>Milogost</i>, based on the element <i>mil</i> ‘gentle, dear’ (from Old Slavic <i>milъ</i>); compare 3 below.","North German: from a pet form of the personal name   Miele   4, of ancient Germanic origin."]},{"name":"Milks","meanings":["English: variant of   Milk  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Lochore of that Ilk, Knight was born in 1263, in Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, his father, Michael Wemyss - Lord of Wemyss, was 32 and his mother, Agatha Lochore, was 23. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1325, in Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1295–1342":"1295–1342","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1231–1319":"1231–1319","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1325":"1325","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1319":"1319","Coaltown of Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Wemyss, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland"},"fi":{"1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1295–1342":"1295–1342","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1231–1319":"1231–1319","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1325":"1325","about 1325":"noin 1325","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1319":"1319","Coaltown of Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Wemyss, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland"},"fr":{"1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1295–1342":"1295–1342","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1231–1319":"1231–1319","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1325":"1325","about 1325":"environ 1325","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","129